The Scrambler generates the same pseudo-noise code as in Modulation1 and demodulates the received signal. We assume we can estimate the channel perfectly. (This is the job of a channel estimator by sending pilot bits.) In this case, user1's signal has 3 paths: {0.5, 0.3, 0.2}
Signal via the 2nd path arrives at the receiver one SampleDelay behind the 1st path. Therefore, it should be demodulated by a PN code that is also one SampleDelayed. It can be separated from signals of path1 and path3 because a shifted PN code is nearly orthogonal to itself. Signal via the 3rd path is operated in similar ways.
We then "collect" these signals from different paths so the SINR is higher than if we do equalization etc. Signals are added together with different weight. The weight is proportional to the path gain since we always want to rely more on the "strong" path.
